, Otto, Erhard, Hans, Heinz, Aloys, Bodo, Erna, Ernst, Frieda, Friedhelm, Hanni.","English (West Country): habitational name from any of the forty or so places in southwestern England called Beer(e) or Bear(e). Most of these derive their names from the West Saxon dative case, <i>beara</i>, of Old English <i>bearu</i> ‘grove, wood’ (the standard Old English dative <i>bearwe</i> being preserved in   Barrow  ). In some cases the surname may be topographic in origin, from <i>atte beare</i> ‘at the grove’. Some may be from Middle English <i>bere</i> ‘woodland swine-pasture’ (Old English <i>bǣr</i>). Compare   Bear   1.","English: variant of   Bear   2 ‘bear’."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":0,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":25,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabel Bere was born about 1290, in Cornwall, England, her father, Richard de La Bere, was 20 and her mother, Sybil Chabbonare, was 20. She married Sir John Arundell II about 1310, in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1320, in St Mawgan, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 31."},"et":{"about 1290–1320":"umbes 1290–1320","1290–1320":"1290–1320","1295–1366":"1295–1366","1294–1379":"1294–1379","1310–1376":"1310–1376","1272–1385":"1272–1385","1272–1308":"1272–1308","about 1290":"umbes 1290","1385":"1385","1295":"1295","1272":"1272","1294":"1294","Abt 1308":"umbes 1308","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1379":"1379","1366":"1366","1376":"1376","1310":"1310","1320":"1320","about 1310":"umbes 1310","1308":"1308","1317":"1317","Saint Mawgan, Cornwall, England":"St Mawgan, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Tolverne, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","of Tolverne, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lanherne, Cornwall, England":"Lanherne, Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"about 1290–1320":"noin 1290–1320","1290–1320":"1290–1320","1295–1366":"1295–1366","1294–1379":"1294–1379","1310–1376":"1310–1376","1272–1385":"1272–1385","1272–1308":"1272–1308","about 1290":"noin 1290","1385":"1385","1295":"1295","1272":"1272","1294":"1294","Abt 1308":"noin 1308","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1379":"1379","1366":"1366","1376":"1376","1310":"1310","1320":"1320","about 1310":"noin 1310","1308":"1308","1317":"1317","Saint Mawgan, Cornwall, England":"St Mawgan, Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Tolverne, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Wales":"Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of Tolverne, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lanherne, Cornwall, England":"Lanherne, Cornwall, England"},"fr":{"about 1290–1320":"environ 1290–1320","1290–1320":"1290–1320","1295–1366":"1295–1366","1294–1379":"1294–1379","1310–1376":"1310–1376","1272–1385":"1272–1385","1272–1308":"1272–1308",